# Portfolio editing rules

## Ground truth

All factual content must be traceable to one of these files:
- `/Users/nikolaskarefyllidis/Desktop/50_CVs/01 CVs & Cover letters/0000_Rules_and_Skills/CLAUDE_PROFILE.md`
- `/Users/nikolaskarefyllidis/Desktop/50_CVs/01 CVs & Cover letters/0000_Rules_and_Skills/00_KNOWLEDGE_BASE.md`

Read them before writing or editing any content. If a claim cannot be found in either file, do not include it.

## Hallucination rules

- Do not invent technical phrases, method names, or outcomes not present in the ground truth.
- Do not attribute tools or methods to the wrong role or project.
- Do not merge separate projects. hydrAI and the Oxford meanline project are explicitly separate — never describe hydrAI as built on or integrated into the meanline stack.
- Do not overstate seniority, scope, or sole ownership of work beyond what the ground truth states.
- If unsure whether a claim is confirmed, omit it and flag it in a comment.

## hydrAI — hard rules

- hydrAI is **proprietary**. Never add a GitHub link or suggest it is open source.
- hydrAI description must not mention "meanline", "meanline stack", or "meanline aerodynamics".
- Correct framing: Cantera detailed chemistry + PINN/RNN + symbolic regression (SymPy/PyTorch) + CFD coupling + holdout evaluation.
- The `proprietary: true` flag in `_data/projects.yml` must never be removed.

## Separation of projects

These are distinct and must never be merged in descriptions or highlights:
- hydrAI (scientific ML framework) — Visiting Researcher role
- Oxford meanline code (multi-stage aerodynamics tool with Cantera chemistry) — separate bullet in Visiting Researcher, or separate project card
- Turbo-Reactor Pilot Validation (3D unsteady CFD, plant validation) — Coolbrook role

## Public code

Only one public GitHub repo exists: `github.com/karefyllidis/black-box-optimization`. Do not add GitHub links to any other project.

## Content constraints

- Do not fabricate publications, employers, awards, or degrees.
- Do not add a military/Raider Forces entry — it is not present on the portfolio by design.
- Do not add salary, filter rules, or application history anywhere on the site.
- The contact section contains only a one-line location/collaboration statement — no duplicate link lists.

## Style constraints

- Tone: professional academic/engineering portfolio. Not generic AI portfolio template language.
- No "passionate about", "cutting-edge", "state-of-the-art", "transformational".
- No "responsible for" — use active verbs (led, built, developed, ran, designed).
- No "supported" or "contributed to" — these strip agency.
- No invented CV-speak: "structured evidence frameworks", "deployment-ready outcomes", "disconnected streams".

## Jekyll / file rules

- Do not edit `vendor/`, `Gemfile.lock`, or any built output in `_site/`.
- Do not add new gem dependencies without checking the GitHub Pages whitelist.
- SCSS front matter (`---`) must remain at the top of `assets/css/main.scss`.
- All new images go in `assets/images/`. Use `loading="lazy"` on all `<img>` tags except the hero photo.
- Do not add JavaScript files or inline `<script>` blocks beyond the font-loading `onload` attribute already in `head.html`.

## Minimal diff principle

Prefer the smallest change that achieves the goal. Do not rewrite sections that are not broken. Do not rename files or restructure the Jekyll layout without an explicit instruction.
